<paragraph blockId="13.[151,960,151,177]" box="[151,960,151,177]" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,960,151,177]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,960,151,177]" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">
Discovery of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blandin" baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[314,447,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Morpho" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helenor">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[314,447,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">M. helenor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
populations in Southern Andean Yungas
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="43" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,222,678]" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">
For a long time there were no 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Fruhstorfer" authorityYear="1912" box="[490,580,222,246]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Morpho" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[490,580,222,246]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">Morpho</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens available from the Southern Andean Yungas, but in 1984 Gilbert Lachaume obtained a male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Guerin" authorityYear="1844" box="[490,618,259,283]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Morpho" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="godartii">
<emphasis box="[490,618,259,283]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">M. godartii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from between Muyupampa and Aratial (Sucre-Camiri road), (figured in 
<bibRefCitation author="Blandin, P." box="[151,323,294,318]" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" pagination="11 - 455" refId="ref10029" refString="Blandin, P. (2007 b) The Genus Morpho, Lepidoptera Nymphalidae. Part 3. Addenda to Part 1 and Part 2 &amp; The Subgenera Pessonia, Grasseia, and Morpho. Hillside Books, Canterbury, xi + 99 - 237, figs. 11 - 455." type="book chapter" year="2007">Blandin 2007b</bibRefCitation>
). Since 2001, 
<specimenCount box="[484,585,294,318]" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" type="male">37 males</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[643,765,294,318]" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" type="female">11 females</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blandin" baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[805,929,294,318]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Morpho" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helenor">
<emphasis box="[805,929,294,318]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">M. helenor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected in 13 localities distributed in the Southern Andean Yungas, from Cordillera Province (
<collectingRegion box="[791,917,330,354]" inferredBySuffix="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
dept.), in the north, to Aniceto Arce Province (Tarija dept.) near 
<collectingCountry box="[361,514,366,390]" name="Argentina" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">the Argentine</collectingCountry>
border (Appendix 4). Altitudes vary from 
<quantity box="[997,1069,366,390]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" unit="m" value="500.0">500 m</quantity>
to 
<quantity box="[1105,1191,366,390]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" unit="m" value="1400.0">1400 m</quantity>
a.s.l., with ten localities above 
<quantity box="[273,344,402,426]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" unit="m" value="800.0">800 m</quantity>
a.s.l (
<figureCitation box="[414,477,402,426]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1721,1744]" captionTargetBox="[202,1384,187,1713]" captionTargetId="figure-145@8.[189,1397,165,1739]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Altitudinal distribution of Morpho helenor subspecies." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246407" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246407/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">Fig.4</figureCitation>
). The Southern Andean Yungas form a mosaic of semi-deciduous forest ecosystems, ranging from sub-humid to dry. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blandin" baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[512,634,438,462]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Morpho" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="helenor">
<emphasis box="[512,634,438,462]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">M. helenor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
populations have been found mainly in Sub-humid 
<collectingRegion box="[1220,1325,439,462]" country="Argentina" name="Tucuman" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">Tucuman</collectingRegion>
forests in the upper Subandine belt, but also in Sub-humid forests similar to ecosystems existing in Beni lowlands, and in Chiquitania, in the center of 
<collectingRegion box="[471,594,510,534]" country="Argentina" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">Santa Cruz</collectingRegion>
department (
<figureCitation box="[744,806,510,534]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="14.[151,250,2004,2027]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,330,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-73@14.[151,1436,269,1984]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 9. Map of Southern Yungas ecoregion, showing the ecosystems where Morpho helenor prometa has been collected." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5247395" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5247395/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">Fig.9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,222,678]" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">
These populations differ from both 
<emphasis box="[607,773,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">
M. h. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1866" box="[677,773,547,571]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Morpho" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coelestis">coelestis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[832,1013,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">M. h. theodorus</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1031,1107,546,570]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1799,1822]" captionTargetBox="[240,1323,238,1737]" captionTargetId="figure-106@15.[220,1367,193,1792]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 10. Morpho helenor prometa, ♂ holotype (Yumao, 28.02.2004), recto (a) and verso (b). Morpho helenor prometa, ♀ paratype (El Tordo, 23.02.2004), recto (c) and verso (d)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5246413" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5246413/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="43">Fig.10</figureCitation>
). Males are characterized by wider black margins, particularly on the hindwings (table 5). Females have rather narrow blue bands, with wide margins overlapping the white forewings pupillary points. Overall these specimens exhibit a unique pattern that justifies a new subspecies description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
